    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but i also saw a section about malfunctions. what kind of stuff usually causes the pitot tube to give wrong readings or fail entirely? like is it usually just mechanical stuff or can external things mess with it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Malfunctions can indeed occur with the pitot tube, and they can be caused by a variety of factors. Mechanical issues, such as blockages or damage to the tube itself, can indeed cause problems. However, external factors can also play a significant role. For example, ice accumulation on the pitot tube can significantly reduce or even eliminate airspeed readings, as the ice acts as a barrier to airflow. Similarly, debris or snow on the wing can also interfere with airflow and affect the pitot tube's accuracy. Even more exotic factors, like a sudden gust of wind or a nearby air pocket, can cause the pitot tube to malfunction.",
      "source": "target",
